latestPosts.caption:
Posted @withregram • @archdigestindia Drawing in Metal is the lyrical title of a 10-minute documentary short film capturing the high art that is Vikram Goyal’s (@vikramgoyalstudio) mesmerizing metal design practice. The title perfectly captures the brilliance of the celebrated product designer’s oeuvre, one honed over a two-decade journey of innovation in the decorative arts. Goyal’s ability to mine India’s heritage while simultaneously forging a contemporary visual language has won him accolades both at home and overseas. Last year, he was the first Indian designer to show at Nilufar (@nilufargallery), Nina Yashar’s (@ninayashar) famous design gallery in Milan; recently, he signed on to be represented by the acclaimed Los Angeles–based gallery Future Perfect. Importantly, in a country obsessed with gold, Goyal has elevated a traditional material like brass to a newfound covetable status through his extraordinary artistic interventions. 

What drew Goyal to pushing the boundaries with repoussage was actually quite simple: It was the one technique that allowed him to bring his wild imagination to life. That includes everything from the ornate images of Indian mythology to chinoiserie to abstract organic forms—rendered in everything from furniture to vast wall panels. “Repoussé has allowed me to completely bring to life all these different forms of the visual arts, and is very special because the same amount of time is spent ideating as making the art,” he explains.

Goyal’s new e-commerce venture, Viya (@viyadesignofficial) is a 200-person-strong atelier renowned for its quality, creativity and ability to achieve scale.

latestPosts.caption:
For over 20 years, Vikram Goyal has been redefining Indian design—not with noise, but with nuance.

Rooted in ancestral craftsmanship yet reaching across cultures, his studio in New Delhi is home to over 200 artisans mastering age-old techniques like repoussé, pietra dura, and casting. Originally trained in engineering and economics, Goyal left finance to forge a new path—one of intricate forms, rich textures, and timeless storytelling.

His U.S. debut at Design Miami with The Future Perfect marked a pivotal moment, placing India’s artisanal legacy at the forefront of global collectible design. Each piece is more than an object—it’s a bridge between India’s material past and its design future.

latestPosts.caption:
A rare design convergence is coming to Kolkata—where craftsmanship, mythology, and materiality come alive. Step inside the Burdwan Palace from June 18–21 to witness an extraordinary collaboration between Vikram Goyal Studio and Viya. For the first time ever, the full creative spectrum of both brands is on display—from repoussé deity panels and sculptural brass cabinets to joy-infused contemporary homeware.

A landmark debut in a city celebrated for its cultural soul, this showcase is not just about design—it’s about storytelling carved in metal, stone, and memory.

Read More on Abir Pothi
https://www.abirpothi.com/vikram-goyal-studio-and-viya-present-a-landmark-showcase-in-kolkata/

latestPosts.caption:
Song of the Forest 
The spreading tree limbs of spring time, the bark of the arbour and the colours of the forest are the inspiration behind the Song of the Forest collection, which evokes the Indian mangrove and forest with its shades and textures. This story is brought to life in this floor lamp through a medley of metal forms – both sheet and cast – with semi-precious stones that give voice to the mosaic of the forest.
